<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Shaadhi on 12-12-2001 03:01 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Here are some ideas for you  :)

(as always, Your Milage May Vary  ;))

I have an AMD Thunderbird 800, Geforce2 TI, and my motherboard utilizes the VIA chipset- all that and Win 98, with 512mb memory...

Here is a great utility for managing your memory, pretty important for Win 98, 98SE and ME with lots of memory on board (which we need to run EQ, heh):
 [URL=http://www.outertech.com/downloads.php?product=3&PHPSESSID=f9bad2c5651447bcdfe9c12414038cbc]http://www.outertech.com/downloads.php?product=3&PHPSESSID=f9bad2c5651447bcdfe9c12414038cbc[/URL] 

As far as the drivers go, I'm running the 23.11 drivers, and I'm really happy with them... however, before I did a really, really clean install I did have framerate problems... I actually went in and deleted all traces of the old drivers while in Standard VGA mode before reinstalling the 23.11's and it made quite a difference... 

To do this I removed the drivers in the control panel, rebooted into Standard VGA and did a search on nv*.dll and deleted all that I found, then reinstalled the 23.11 drivers...

The other thing I did, which I think really helped was this:

1) Turned off Virtual Memory
2) Rebooted
3) Defragged the hard drives
4) Turned Virtual Memory back on
5) Rebooted

(to turn off Virtual Memory you can go to System in the Contro Panel, go to the Performance tab and the Virtual Memory access is a button there)

Then I used Cacheman to manage my system memory...

There is a good thread at Monkly Business, too, where I found some of this information:
 [URL=http://pub38.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm1.showMessage?topicID=18608.topic]http://pub38.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm1.showMessage?topicID=18608.topic[/URL] 

Hope this helps...
</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
